justification: Anemia, koilonychia (periungal desquamation), and angular cheilitis (lip cracking) are common symptoms of iron deficiency anemia.}, {diagnosis: Vitamin B12 deficiency anemia
justification: Similar to iron deficiency anemia, B12 deficiency can cause anemia, glossitis (which can manifest as lip cracking), and occasionally edema.}, {diagnosis: Zinc deficiency
justification: Zinc deficiency can lead to impaired wound healing, skin changes like periungal desquamation, and taste changes (which might manifest as lip cracking).}, {diagnosis: Hypothyroidism

justification: Hypothyroidism can cause fatigue (leading to anemia), dry skin, brittle nails (periungal desquamation), and edema.}, {diagnosis: Malabsorption syndromes (e.g., celiac disease, Crohns disease)

justification: Malabsorption can lead to deficiencies in iron, B vitamins, and other nutrients, causing a variety of symptoms including anemia, skin changes, and edema.}, {diagnosis: Congestive heart failure
justification: Foot edema can be a sign of congestive heart failure, and fatigue from heart failure can lead to anemia.}, {diagnosis: Venous insufficiency
justification: This condition can cause edema, particularly in the lower extremities, and skin changes like discoloration and desquamation.}, {diagnosis: Kidney disease
justification: Kidney disease can cause anemia, fluid retention (leading to edema), and electrolyte imbalances that might affect skin and nail health.}, {diagnosis: Medications side effects
justification: Certain medications can cause a wide range of side effects, including anemia, skin reactions, and edema.}, {diagnosis: Biotin deficiency (rare)
justification: Though rare, severe biotin deficiency can cause hair loss, skin changes including periungal desquamation, and cracking of the lips.}
